['200910262', '20091026211', '1444837828', '169462574', '1699467197']
HIF2016_DIS02_CONV26_POST441
8
[I am sure that your Doctor can explain to you in details your complete Ultrasound report., In your first post,you mentioned that the Radiologist stated that the lump may represent a Fibroadenoma but now you say that it's a cyst containing solid components., All I can tell you is that breast cysts can be classified as either simple or complex cysts., Simple Cysts (fluid filled sacs) have virtually no chance of containing malignancy., However,complicated cysts are a little more concerning., They are also fluid filled sacs but contain some solid material (debris)., Usually complicated cysts are aspirated and have the cells examined to better evaluate the nature of the cyst and the majority will results in benign findings when biopsied., I am sorry if I cannot help you more,but I would advise you to visit your Doctor concerning your Ultrasound results,because he/she would be your best source of information.]
7
['1500674914', '547336843', '75058620', '1668911417', '513439370', '206354798', '900987571']
HIF2016_DIS02_CONV27_POST445
5
[Hi.,  Invasive ductal carcinoma cannot be cured by radiation alone.,  At the very least, a mastectomy or lumpectomy (surgery removing a part of the breast along with the tumor) should be done.,  If the tumor is small (less than or equal to 0.5 cm) and no tumor spread to the axillary nodes was found, then radiation treatment after the surgery may suffice.,  But a larger tumor or metastases to the axillary nodes will require the addition of either chemotherapy or hormonal treatment, or both.]
4
